Setting aeide different Masses with rubricated “ Coenelmi,” p. 274, “ Konelmi,’' p. 280, Litanies in the Office of the Dead prove, clearly, a book made for a Benedictine Ghureh, and where SS. Peter and Oenelm had a particular cult. Winchcomb Abbey was famous as the burial-place of St. Cenelm, and the Church hard by was dedicated to St. Peter.

Finally there is the relationship between Fleury and Winchcomb. Oswald Bishop of Worcester and Archbishop of York reconstructed the latter Monastery and confided it to the Abbat Germain, about A.D. 985, and fetched him from Fleury to be his fellow worker in its restoration. The writing is of the school of the three Benedictionals of St. Ethelwold, Archbishop Robert, and of Ramsay. Little gold is used. The initials are mostly red, blue and green, like to those of the Ramsay MS.
